  {
    "type": "message",
    "subtype": "thread_broadcast",
    "text": "Basically, I'm starting to realize that there's an infinite number of ways to break me that I can never anticipate in advance. Using software from an independent vendor who can push arbitrary updates to your device is increasingly like making a deal with a demon who's parsing the language of your agreements in the most antagonistic way possible.\n\nSo no, it's not a promise not to break you. I independently think breaking compatibility is often a _good_ thing for all parties that we don't explore enough. What it is is an offering of _ongoing control_ in exchange for a clear line of communications.\n\nThe metaphor you use matters a lot here. This isn't about division of labor in a factory. This is about being allies in a war.",
    "user": "UCUSW7WVD",
    "ts": "1538879108.000100",
    "thread_ts": "1538877442.000100",
    "root": {
      "client_msg_id": "5972efea-83e6-434e-859d-554959eea25a",
      "type": "message",
      "text": "Interesting; so you’re basically asking users to pay in labor in exchange for a “we won’t break you” promise + other goodies",
